Case Study: Bellabeat

Mharie Brigham

May 2024

Scenario:

Bellabeat is a high-tech manufacturer of health-focused products for women. They have asked for an analysis of smart device fitness data to highlight new growth opportunities for the company. The stakeholders include the Bellabeat cofounders and marketing analytics team. The products to analyze include the Bellabeat app, the Leaf wellness tracker, the Time wellness watch, the Spring water bottle, and the Bellabeat membership program.

Bellabeat App

Provides health data related to their activity, sleep, stress, menstrual cycle, and mindfulness habits. The app connects to Bellabeat smart wellness products

Leaf

Can be worn as a bracelet, necklace, or clip and tracks activity, sleep, and stress.

Time

Smart watch that tracks user activity, sleep, and stress.

Spring

Smart water bottle that tracks daily water intake.

Bellabeat membership

Subscription-based membership program that gives users 24/7 access to fully personalized guidance on nutrition, activity, sleep, health and beauty, and mindfulness based on their lifestyle and goals.

Business Task:

Identify trends in smart device usage, determine applicability to Bellabeat customer base and products, and recommend marketing strategies.

Dataset:

Since we have no data directly from Bellabeat, third-party data from FitBit customers will be used. Both Bellabeat and FitBit have similar products and customer bases.

Mobius. (2016). FitBit Fitness Tracker Data, Version 2. Retrieved 5.16.24 from (https://zenodo.org/records/53894#.ZAiD4XbMJPa)

This dataset was generated from survey responses and contains personal fitness tracker information from thirty consenting FitBit users. This is an open-source dataset under the copyright law CC0. While this is an outdated data set (from 2016) it will still serve the purposes of this case study. The most useful files in this data set will be the dailyActivity_merged.csv and the minuteSleep_merged.csv since Bellabeats products generate similar information. These data tables are organized in a long format.

Limitations

There is no demographic information with this data set, nor is there any geographic information provided. There is no indication of the ages, sexes, lifestyles, or locations of these thirty individuals, all of which could have an impact on the health data provided. Additionally, the time frame of the survey data is two months. There are outliers throughout this data set, likely due to human error, data collection error, and miscalculations in the data.

Tools

R will be used to clean, analyze, and visualize the data for this case study for its statistical analysis power. The packages used include tidyverse, janitor, skimr, dplyr, and ggforce,

Transforming Data:

Creating a new data frame to for the number of hours slept each night:

# Sleep Minutes to Hours Slept per Night by User
hoursleep<-minutesleep%>%
  mutate(datenew=as.Date(mdy_hms(date)))%>%
  mutate(minutes=1)%>%
  aggregate(minutes~datenew+Id,FUN=sum)%>%
  mutate(hours=minutes/60)
  head(hoursleep)

Creating a new data frame for the average distance by activity level intensity:

# Average total distance by average activity level
distintenseavg<-dailyactivity%>%
  group_by(Id)%>%
  mutate('AvgTotalDistance'=mean(TotalDistance),'AvgVeryActiveDistance'=mean(VeryActiveDistance),'AvgModeratelyActiveDistance'=mean(ModeratelyActiveDistance),'AvgLightActiveDistance'=mean(LightActiveDistance),'Idstr'=as.character(Id))%>%
  group_by(Idstr)%>%
  select(Idstr,AvgVeryActiveDistance,AvgModeratelyActiveDistance,AvgLightActiveDistance)%>%
  distinct()%>%
  pivot_longer(cols=c('AvgVeryActiveDistance','AvgModeratelyActiveDistance','AvgLightActiveDistance'),names_to='ActivityType',values_to='Distance')

Creating a new frame for the average time spent at each activity level intensity:

# Average total activity intensity minutes
minintenseavg<-dailyactivity%>%
  mutate('AvgSedentaryMinutes'=mean(SedentaryMinutes),'AvgVeryActiveMinutes'=mean(VeryActiveMinutes),'AvgFairlyActiveMinutes'=mean(FairlyActiveMinutes),'AvgLightlyActiveMinutes'=mean(LightlyActiveMinutes))%>%
  select(AvgSedentaryMinutes,AvgVeryActiveMinutes,AvgFairlyActiveMinutes,AvgLightlyActiveMinutes)%>%
  distinct()%>%
  pivot_longer(cols=c('AvgVeryActiveMinutes','AvgFairlyActiveMinutes','AvgLightlyActiveMinutes','AvgSedentaryMinutes'),names_to='ActivityType',values_to='Minutes')%>%
  mutate(Minutes=round(Minutes,digits=2))

Creating a new frame to merge hours slept per night with daily activity:

# Merging sleep hours and daily activity - remove Id's without sleep data
dailyactivitynewdate <- dailyactivity%>%
  mutate(datenew=as.Date(mdy(ActivityDate)))
combineddata <- merge(hoursleep,dailyactivitynewdate, by=c('Id','datenew'))%>%
  select(-ActivityDate)

Correlations and Visualizations:

Total Steps v. Sedentary Minutes

ggplot(dailyactivity)+
  geom_point(aes(x=TotalSteps, y=SedentaryMinutes))+
  ggtitle("Total Steps v. Sedentary Minutes")+
  xlab("Total Steps")+
  ylab("Sedentary Minutes")

# Correlation Test
cor.test(dailyactivity$TotalSteps,dailyactivity$SedentaryMinutes, method=c('pearson'))
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation

## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.3673722 -0.1987306
## sample estimates:
##        cor 
## -0.2852577

There is a significant negative correlation between sedentary minutes and total steps. The less minutes spent sedentary, the more steps taken per day.

Activity Intensity Breakdown

ggplot()+
  xlab('Activity Type')+
  ylab('Average Minutes')+
  ggtitle('Activity Intensity by Minutes')+
  geom_col(data=minintenseavg,mapping=aes(x=fct_rev(fct_reorder(ActivityType,Minutes)),y=Minutes, fill=ActivityType))+
  scale_fill_manual(name='Activity Intensity',values=c('blue','chartreuse3','cyan3','red'),labels=c('Fairly','Lightly','Sedentary','Very'))+
  geom_text(data=minintenseavg, mapping=aes(x=fct_rev(fct_reorder(ActivityType,Minutes)), y=Minutes, label=Minutes), hjust=c(0,0,0,.75))+
  coord_flip()

On average, users spend about 995.28 minutes sedentaryabout 16.6 hours each day. Based on summary statistics from our sleep data, the average person sleeps approximately 7.5 hours per night. If 7.5 of these 16.6 sedentary hours are spent sleeping, the average person is still spending about 9.1 hours awake and not active.

Findings and Recommendations:

Findings:

Based on all of these visualizations, we have learned the following:

  • There is a significant negative correlation between total steps and sedentary minutes; the more steps taken, the less time spent sedentary
  • There is a significant positive correlation between total distance walked and total calories burned; the greater the distance, the more calories burned.
  • On average, a users total daily distance consists mostly of a light intensity activity level
  • On average, a user spends 7.5 hours sleeping per night
  • On average, a user spends 13.07 minutes being fairly active, 16.62 minutes being very active, 170.07 minute being lightly active, and 995.28 minutes being sedentary (including sleeping)
  • There is no significant correlation between total daily distance or total daily calories burned, and hours slept.

Recommendations:

By applying this FitBit data to the Bellabeat customer base, there are several areas to focus marketing strategies. Marketing strategies to increase awareness of their health habits may increase device usage.

Since the only available data is direct information from smart watch bioinformatics, it is difficult to make accurate recommendations on improving users app interactions, membership experience, or water intake. Additional data would be required to develop concrete solutions on exactly which aspects of the app and membership could be improved to benefit marketing strategies and device usage.

On average, users spend approximately 9.1 hours awake and sedentary. Push notifications to encourage light activity throughout the day could increase Bellabeat App usage. Offering personalized insights into users sedentary habits could increase Time smart watch usage, Leaf smart clip usage, and Bellabeat memberships to provide individualized reminder schedules, nutritional guidance, and light activity programs.
